{
  "What is diffraction?": "",
  "Restricting light oscillations to a single plane using a filter": "",
  "Bouncing of light waves off a surface back into the same medium": "",
  "Conversion of light energy into thermal energy within a material": "",
  "Bending and spreading of waves around obstacles or through openings": "",
  "Diffraction is the bending and spreading of waves around obstacles or through openings. It is most noticeable when the opening size is comparable to the wavelength.": "",
  "When is diffraction most significant?": "",
  "When the opening is very large": "",
  "At very high frequencies": "",
  "In a vacuum": "",
  "When the opening is comparable to the wavelength": "",
  "Diffraction is most significant when the size of the opening or obstacle is comparable to the wavelength of the wave. Much larger openings produce minimal diffraction.": "",
  "Condition for bright fringes in Young's double slit:": "",
  "d = nλ": "",
  "d sin θ = (n+½)λ": "",
  "d cos θ = nλ": "",
  "d sin θ = nλ": "",
  "Bright fringes (constructive interference) occur when d sin θ = nλ, where n = 0, 1, 2... This is when the path difference is a whole number of wavelengths.": "",
  "What is a diffraction grating?": "",
  "A curved reflective surface that focuses light to a single point": "",
  "A device with many parallel slits producing sharp bright maxima": "",
  "A transparent filter that selectively transmits certain wavelengths": "",
  "A single narrow opening used to produce a central bright fringe": "",
  "A diffraction grating has many closely spaced parallel slits. The large number of slits produces very sharp, well-defined bright maxima, useful for analyzing light spectra.": "",
  "In single-slit diffraction, which maximum is brightest?": "",
  "The central maximum": "",
  "The edges": "",
  "The first side maximum": "",
  "They are all equal": "",
  "In single-slit diffraction, the central maximum is the brightest and widest. Secondary maxima on either side are progressively dimmer and narrower.": "",
  "What is the formula for fringe spacing?": "",
  "Δy = λL/d": "",
  "Δy = dL/λ": "",
  "Δy = λd/L": "",
  "Δy = d/(λL)": "",
  "Fringe spacing Δy = λL/d, where λ is wavelength, L is the distance to the screen, and d is the slit separation. Wider spacing occurs with longer wavelengths or narrower slit separations.": "",
  "What must two sources be for interference to occur?": "",
  "Coherent": "",
  "Incoherent": "",
  "Very bright": "",
  "The same color only": "",
  "For a stable interference pattern, the two sources must be coherent — meaning they have the same frequency and a constant phase relationship.": "",
  "What happens when two wave crests meet at the same point?": "",
  "They cancel each other out completely": "",
  "They combine to make a larger amplitude wave": "",
  "They pass through without any interaction": "",
  "They reflect off each other and reverse direction": "",
  "When two crests (or two troughs) meet, constructive interference occurs — the amplitudes add together, producing a wave with greater amplitude than either individual wave.": "",
  "What happens when a wave crest meets a wave trough?": "",
  "The waves combine to produce a louder sound wave": "",
  "The waves reflect off each other in opposite directions": "",
  "The waves cancel each other out partially or completely": "",
  "The waves merge permanently into a single combined wave": "",
  "When a crest meets a trough, destructive interference occurs. If the amplitudes are equal, they cancel completely, producing zero displacement. Otherwise, partial cancellation occurs.": "",
  "What produces the pattern of bright and dark fringes in Young's experiment?": "",
  "Light reflecting off the edges of the slits themselves": "",
  "Different colors of light separating through the slit gap": "",
  "Constructive and destructive interference of light waves": "",
  "Shadows cast by the barrier between the two narrow slits": "",
  "The bright fringes are where light from both slits arrives in phase (constructive interference), while dark fringes are where the light arrives out of phase (destructive interference).": "",
  "What is 'constructive interference'?": "",
  "When waves combine to produce a wave with smaller amplitude": "",
  "When waves combine to produce a wave with larger amplitude": "",
  "When waves pass through each other without any change at all": "",
  "When one wave completely absorbs the energy of another wave": "",
  "Constructive interference occurs when two waves are in phase (crests align with crests) and their amplitudes add together, producing a combined wave with larger amplitude.": "",
  "What is 'destructive interference'?": "",
  "When waves combine and their amplitudes cancel each other out": "",
  "When waves combine and produce a larger resulting amplitude": "",
  "When a wave is destroyed by hitting a solid barrier surface": "",
  "When light waves change into heat energy upon contact with matter": "",
  "Destructive interference occurs when two waves are out of phase (crest meets trough) and their amplitudes subtract, reducing or eliminating the combined wave amplitude.": "",
  "What does 'coherent' mean when describing light sources?": "",
  "The sources have the same brightness and intensity level": "",
  "The sources emit all colors of the visible spectrum equally": "",
  "The sources have the same frequency and a constant phase difference": "",
  "The sources are positioned at the same distance from a detector": "",
  "Coherent light sources have the same frequency and maintain a constant phase relationship over time. This is essential for producing a stable, observable interference pattern.": "",
  "What is 'path difference' in the context of interference?": "",
  "The difference in distance traveled by two waves from their sources to a point": "",
  "The difference in speed between two waves in different media types": "",
  "The difference in frequency between two waves from different sources": "",
  "The difference in amplitude between two interfering wave crests": "",
  "Path difference is the difference in the distance each wave travels from its source to a given point. Whether interference is constructive or destructive depends on whether this difference is a whole number of wavelengths or a half-number.": "",
  "What is meant by an 'interference pattern'?": "",
  "A random scattering of light in all directions from a rough surface": "",
  "A regular arrangement of bright and dark bands from overlapping waves": "",
  "A single bright spot formed by focusing light through a lens system": "",
  "A continuous spectrum of colors produced by a glass prism device": "",
  "An interference pattern is the regular arrangement of bright (constructive) and dark (destructive) bands or fringes produced when two or more coherent waves overlap.": "",
  "What is a 'fringe' in an interference or diffraction pattern?": "",
  "The edge of a shadow cast by an opaque straight barrier": "",
  "A bright or dark band in the pattern caused by wave interaction": "",
  "The border around a lens where light is blocked from passing": "",
  "The central opening in a barrier through which waves pass": "",
  "A fringe is one of the alternating bright or dark bands in an interference or diffraction pattern. Bright fringes correspond to constructive interference and dark fringes to destructive interference.": "",
  "What does the term 'wavelength' mean?": "",
  "The height of a wave measured from its rest position to its peak": "",
  "The distance between two consecutive crests or troughs of a wave": "",
  "The number of wave cycles that pass a point every second of time": "",
  "The speed at which a wave moves through a particular medium": "",
  "Wavelength is the distance between two consecutive identical points on a wave, such as crest to crest or trough to trough. It is usually measured in meters and symbolized by λ.": "",
  "What does 'monochromatic' mean when describing light?": "",
  "Light that contains all visible colors mixed together equally": "",
  "Light that consists of a single wavelength or color only": "",
  "Light that has been polarized to vibrate in only one plane": "",
  "Light that travels in perfectly parallel rays without spreading": "",
  "Monochromatic light consists of a single wavelength (and therefore a single color). Lasers produce highly monochromatic light, which is ideal for interference and diffraction experiments.": "",
  "What is 'superposition' of waves?": "",
  "When one wave completely replaces another wave at a point": "",
  "When two waves overlap and their displacements add together": "",
  "When a wave bounces off a barrier and reverses its direction": "",
  "When a wave changes speed as it enters a different medium": "",
  "The principle of superposition states that when two or more waves overlap, the resulting displacement at any point is the sum of the individual displacements. This is the basis of both constructive and destructive interference.": "",
  "What does 'in phase' mean for two waves?": "",
  "The waves have different frequencies but the same amplitude": "",
  "The waves reach their crests and troughs at the same time": "",
  "The waves travel in opposite directions through the medium": "",
  "The waves have the same speed but different wavelengths": "",
  "Two waves are in phase when their crests and troughs align at the same time and place. This condition leads to constructive interference and maximum combined amplitude.": "",
  "A student shines a laser through a narrow single slit and sees a pattern of bright and dark bands on a screen. What causes the dark bands?": "",
  "The slit edges block some of the laser light from reaching the screen": "",
  "Parts of the diffracted wave cancel out through destructive interference": "",
  "The screen absorbs certain wavelengths of the laser light selectively": "",
  "The laser beam splits into separate beams that miss parts of the screen": "",
  "In single-slit diffraction, light from different parts of the slit travels different distances to points on the screen. At certain angles, these waves are out of phase and cancel each other through destructive interference, creating dark bands.": "",
  "In a lab, a student increases the slit separation in a double-slit experiment. What happens to the fringe spacing on the screen?": "",
  "The fringe spacing increases because the slits are farther apart": "",
  "The fringe spacing decreases because Δy = λL/d and d increased": "",
  "The fringe spacing stays the same regardless of slit separation": "",
  "The fringes disappear completely when the slits move farther apart": "",
  "Fringe spacing Δy = λL/d. Since d is in the denominator, increasing slit separation d decreases fringe spacing. The bright and dark bands become closer together.": "",
  "A student uses red light and then blue light in a double-slit experiment. How does the fringe pattern change?": "",
  "Blue light produces wider spaced fringes because it has more energy": "",
  "Blue light produces narrower spaced fringes because it has shorter wavelength": "",
  "Both lights produce identical fringe patterns with the same spacing": "",
  "Blue light produces no fringes because it cannot be diffracted at all": "",
  "Since Δy = λL/d, shorter wavelength (blue) produces smaller fringe spacing. Red light (longer wavelength) produces more widely spaced fringes than blue light.": "",
  "A student notices that sound can be heard around corners but light cannot bend around corners in the same way. Why?": "",
  "Sound is a wave but light is not a wave so it cannot diffract at all": "",
  "Sound has much longer wavelengths comparable to doorway sizes causing more diffraction": "",
  "Light travels too fast to bend around corners while sound is slow enough": "",
  "Sound reflects off walls while light is absorbed by the wall material": "",
  "Diffraction is most significant when the wavelength is comparable to the opening size. Sound wavelengths (centimeters to meters) are similar to doorway sizes, so sound diffracts easily. Light wavelengths (hundreds of nanometers) are far too small for noticeable diffraction around everyday objects.": "",
  "A student views a CD under white light and sees rainbow-like colors. What optical phenomenon causes this?": "",
  "The CD acts as a prism and refracts light through its plastic material": "",
  "The CD surface acts as a diffraction grating separating wavelengths": "",
  "The metallic coating on the CD filters out certain colors of light": "",
  "The CD surface polarizes white light into separate color components": "",
  "The closely spaced grooves on a CD surface act like a diffraction grating. Different wavelengths of white light are diffracted at different angles, producing the rainbow pattern of colors.": "",
  "In a lab, a student moves the screen farther from the double slits. What happens to the fringe spacing?": "",
  "The fringe spacing increases because Δy = λL/d and L increased": "",
  "The fringe spacing decreases because the screen is farther away": "",
  "The fringe spacing stays exactly the same at every screen distance": "",
  "The fringes disappear entirely when the screen is moved too far away": "",
  "Since Δy = λL/d, increasing the screen distance L increases the fringe spacing proportionally. The bright and dark bands spread farther apart.": "",
  "A student uses a diffraction grating to analyze light from a gas lamp. They observe distinct colored lines. What does this tell them about the gas?": "",
  "The gas is extremely hot and emitting white light at all wavelengths": "",
  "The gas emits light at specific wavelengths unique to its composition": "",
  "The grating creates artificial colors that are not actually in the light": "",
  "The gas absorbs all colors except the ones seen through the grating": "",
  "Each element emits light at characteristic wavelengths. The diffraction grating separates these wavelengths into distinct lines, allowing identification of the gas — this is the basis of spectroscopy.": "",
  "A student designs noise-canceling headphones. Which wave principle do they rely on?": "",
  "Constructive interference to amplify desired sounds only": "",
  "Destructive interference to cancel out unwanted noise waves": "",
  "Diffraction to bend sound waves away from the listener's ears": "",
  "Refraction to redirect noise waves around the headphone casing": "",
  "Noise-canceling headphones use microphones to detect ambient noise and produce sound waves that are out of phase (inverted) with the noise. When these waves overlap, destructive interference reduces or eliminates the unwanted sound.": "",
  "A student observes that when they make the single slit narrower, the central bright band gets wider. Why?": "",
  "A narrower slit lets more light through, so the band spreads out more": "",
  "A narrower slit causes greater diffraction and more spreading of waves": "",
  "A narrower slit focuses the light beam into a broader parallel beam": "",
  "A narrower slit changes the wavelength of the light passing through": "",
  "When the slit width decreases and becomes more comparable to the wavelength, diffraction effects increase. Greater diffraction causes the light to spread out more, resulting in a wider central maximum.": "",
  "A student sets up Young's double-slit experiment and counts 10 bright fringes on the screen. If they switch from green light to red light, what changes?": "",
  "More fringes fit on the screen because red light has a shorter wavelength": "",
  "Fewer fringes fit on the screen because red light has a longer wavelength": "",
  "The same number of fringes appear because color does not affect spacing": "",
  "No fringes appear because red light cannot produce interference patterns": "",
  "Red light has a longer wavelength than green light, so it produces wider fringe spacing (Δy = λL/d). With wider spacing, fewer fringes fit on the same screen.": ""
}